 "blurb": "The mid-2000s arena phenomenon — the BK Lounge / MySpace-era comic who pulled stand-up into 18,000-seat venues and broke the post-Steve Martin selling record at Madison Square Garden.",
 "bio": "Dane Cook is the most important commercial story in 21st-century American stand-up — and one of the most contested. Working out of Boston in the late 1990s, he turned an aggressive online presence (a MySpace page with millions of friends before that meant anything) into a touring scale no comedian had attempted since Steve Martin's '70s arena run. Harmful If Swallowed (2003) and Retaliation (2005) — the latter the highest-charting comedy album in 28 years, certified platinum — built a young, suburban, mostly male audience that knew the bits by heart: The BK Lounge, the Atheist Sneeze, the Friend That Nobody Likes. Then Vicious Circle (HBO, 2006) and Rough Around the Edges: Live from Madison Square Garden (2007) put him in front of a sold-out MSG, the second comic ever to fill it after Andrew Dice Clay. The backlash was as loud as the boom — accusations of joke theft, peers calling the work shallow — but the commercial achievement and the era it defined are not in dispute.",
